   - Undefined behavior with ctype (affects correctness/DoS): all uses of std::isspace/std::isprint(ch) in parsing states and chartoprint; reason: passing signed char with value < 0 is UB, leading to misclassification or crashes.
   - CWE-117 (Log injection – low severity): log_debug/log_warn print attacker-controlled header names/values; reason: control chars/newlines can forge logs if log processing is naive.

1. YES
2. - CWE-326: Inadequate minimum key size enforcement. Vulnerable lines: In InvertibleRWFunction::GenerateRandom: "int modulusSize = 2048; alg.GetIntValue(...);" and "if (modulusSize < 16) throw InvalidArgument(...);". Reason: Allows caller to generate keys as small as 16 bits, enabling trivial factorization; enforce a strong minimum (e.g., >= 2048 or policy-bound).
   - CWE-208/CWE-385 (Timing/Side-channel): Data-dependent branches and OpenMP in private-key ops. Vulnerable lines: In InvertibleRWFunction::CalculateInverse: "if (Jacobi(...) != 1) { cp = cp.IsOdd() ? ...; cq = cq.IsOdd() ? ...; }", "#pragma omp parallel ... sections ... cp = ModularSquareRoot(...); cq = ModularSquareRoot(...);", and "y = STDMIN(y, m_n-y);" plus "if (ApplyFunction(y) != x) ...". Reason: Variable-time control flow and parallel scheduling can leak timing; blinding helps but does not eliminate side-channels—prefer constant-time paths and avoid OpenMP in sensitive code.
   - CWE-20 (Insufficient input validation on decoded keys): No immediate consistency checks during decode. Vulnerable lines: In InvertibleRWFunction::BERDecode: "m_n.BERDecode(seq); m_p.BERDecode(seq); m_q.BERDecode(seq); m_u.BERDecode(seq);". Reason: Accepts untrusted key components without verifying m_p, m_q primality and m_u correctness at decode time; using such keys without calling Validate(level>=1/2) can cause insecure or undefined behavior.
